The '''Morocco national football team''' ({{langx|ar|منتخب المغرب لكرة القدم}}; {{Langx|zgh|ⵜⴰⵔⴰⴱⴱⵓⵜ ⵜⴰⵏⴰⵎⵓⵔⵜ ⵜⴰⵎⵖⵔⵉⴱⵉⵜ ⵏ ⵜⵛⴰⵎⵎⴰ ⵏ ⵓⴹⴰⵕ}}) represents [[Morocco]] in men's international [[Association football|football]]. It is controlled by the [[Royal Moroccan Football Federation]] (FRMF), the governing body for [[football in Morocco]]. It has been affiliated with [[FIFA]] since 1960, with the [[Confederation of African Football]] since 1959, and with the [[UNAF|Union of North African Football]] since 2005. The team, which is known as the ''Atlas Lions'', plays home matches at the [[Prince Moulay Abdellah Stadium]] in [[Rabat]], and trains at the Mohammed VI Football Complex in [[Salé]].

Morocco is regarded as one of Africa’s most successful national football teams. They have won five continental titles, including the [[1976 African Cup of Nations|1976]] and [[2025 African Cup of Nations|2025]] editions of the [[Africa Cup of Nations|African Cup of Nations]]. They won the [[African Nations Championship]] in [[2018 African Nations Championship|2018]], [[2020 African Nations Championship|2020]] and [[2024 African Nations Championship|2024]]. Morocco has qualified for the [[FIFA World Cup]] on seven occasions. In [[1986 FIFA World Cup|1986]], they made history as the first African team to win a World Cup group and advance to the [[1986 FIFA World Cup knockout stage|knockout stage]]. At the [[2022 FIFA World Cup|2022 World Cup]], Morocco became the first African and first Arab team to reach a World Cup semi-final. They were also the third World Cup semi-finalist from outside [[UEFA|Europe]] or [[CONMEBOL|South America]]. In 2025, Morocco set a [[List of world association football records|world record]] for the longest winning streak in international football, achieving 19 consecutive victories across all competitions.

Morocco was ranked 10th in the [[FIFA World Rankings]] in April 1998. They were Africa’s highest-ranked national team for three consecutive years, from 1997 to 1999, and have occupied that position again since December 2022. {{As of|2026|06|04}}, Morocco is ranked 7th in the world, the highest ranking by an African team since [[Nigeria national football team|Nigeria]] in 1994.

Morocco is set to become the second African nation, the second [[MENA]] nation, and the first North African nation to host the FIFA World Cup, after being chosen as a co-host for the [[2030 FIFA World Cup|2030 edition]] alongside Portugal and Spain.